The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Sunday, August 22, 2004 				 Hard line on truckers
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, Aug. 21: The indefinite nationwide truckers strike against the imposition of service tax elicited a mixed response on the first day today.																								The government on its part adopted a hard line, asking the All-India Motor Transport Congress to call off the strike if talks are to continue.																								In Bengal, the strike is reported to be total with over seven lakh trucks going off the roads. Owners of about 60,000 trucks registered in Orissa have also stopped plying their vehicles. 																								In Tripura, the strike did not have any impact as the truck owners did not join the strike due to the states the virtual suspension of its rail link with Assam for the last two months. 																								The strike is reported to be near total in Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Uttar Pradesh, Karnataka and Orissa.																								Inter-state movement of goods was hit in Gujarat, Bihar and Assam. However, the strike had only a minor impact in Jammu and Kashmir, most north-eastern states, Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Goa and Himachal Pradesh , according to information from the control room set up here to monitor the strike. Haryana, Punjab, and Maharashtra witnessed a partial response. 																								The Gujarat and Delhi governments have invoked the Essential Supplies Maintenance Act in order to keep vegetable and fruit prices in check. 																								B.. Dhumal, the president of the motor transport congress, the apex body of truckers which has given the strike call, claimed that 95 per cent of the 40 lakh trucks were off the roads today. We have exempted trucks carrying essential commodities for the next three days, he said. 																								Senior officials of the finance ministry are reported to have asked the truckers to call off the strike if they wanted to continue the talks. 																								A motor transport congress office-bearer said: We refused to accept this pre-condition for talks. 
